# Web Application Protocol Identification - HTTPS

## Objective

The goal of this task was to:

* Start the Debian VM
* Connect to it via SSH
* Start the Apache web server
* Identify the protocol used by the vulnerable web application

---

## Initial Information

The lab specifies that the web application is located at:

/var/www/https/

This path is important for understanding how the application is served.

---

## Understanding URL Structure

A standard URL follows this format:

protocol://IP-address/path

Examples:

* http://192.168.1.10
* https://192.168.1.10
* ftp://192.168.1.10

The protocol is the part before "://".

---

## Key Observation

The directory name:

/var/www/https/

strongly indicates that the application is configured to run over HTTPS.

---

## Apache Behavior

Apache typically serves web applications as follows:

* Port 80 → HTTP
* Port 443 → HTTPS

When a directory is specifically named "https", it usually corresponds to a secure virtual host configuration.

---

## Verification Steps

After connecting via SSH:

ssh student@<target-ip>

Start Apache:

sudo systemctl start apache2

Then verify the protocol using:

curl -k https://<target-ip>

Or access via browser:

https://<target-ip>

---

## Conclusion

Based on:

* Directory naming (/var/www/https/)
* Apache configuration patterns
* Standard protocol usage

The vulnerable web application is running on:

HTTPS

---

## Additional Note

If unsure about the protocol in a real scenario, it can be confirmed using:

nmap -sV <target-ip>

Typical output:

* 80/tcp → http
* 443/tcp → https
